Hello, $name <face:neu_neu>
Welcome to the branch test.
Below will branch on the 'test' condition.
[match:test]
    =a
        We detected a!
    =b
        We should not see this
[/match]
This is now the fallback of the match.
Let's go into the next test.
Can we match in an option? {
    ?: I hope so! 
        [match:testb]
            =b
                Detected b!
            =c
                We should no see this.
        [/match]
}
This is a fallback for the option, hopefully the match falls into this too!
Next, lets make sure our match just runs into the fallback when nothing hits.
[match:testx]
    =y
        We should not see this
    =a
        We should not see this either
[/match]
This is the fallback we should see!
Can a match lead to a goto?
[match:test]
    =a
        -> onA
    =b
        How.
[/match]
Fallback we should not see

@onA
This is the result of the goto we should hit.
What about chained matches?
[match:test]
    =x
        Should not see this
[/match]
[match:testb]
    =b
        Detected b, because test a failed first
[/match]
And what about nested matches?
[match:test]
    =a
        [match:testb]
            =b
                Got to b through a nested match
        [/match]
[/match]
Also have a fallback here, our nested match should connect.
Lastly, the weirdest edge case. Sometimes we might have a nested match that is chained.
# In this case, the nested match should fallback/treat the outers chain as it's own chain too...
[match:test]
    =a
        # We should enter this test, but then it will fail and should chain to the outers chain...
        [match:testx]
            =fail
                We should not see this
        [/match]
[/match]
[match:testb]
    =b
        We should hit this b detect
[/match]
And *then* this is the last fallback for this annoying thing.
But alas, that last test is if the matches are directly owned by the cases. What happens when there's a sequence first?
[match:test]
    =a
        Wow we're in a right now, 
        but then there's a sequence
        and only now there's a nested match...
        [match:testx]
            =fail
                We should not see this
        [/match]
[/match]
[match:testb]
    =b
        We should hit this b from our chain.
[/match]
Similar, final fallback for everything here.
We should also make sure the match fallback inheritance also works when at the end of an option stream. {
    ?: Agreed & Match that passes
